inputs_used.system_design:
Objective: Build a scalable, secure, and high-performing website with CMS capabilities, marketing pages, blog, user accounts, and optional e-commerce. Meet WCAG 2.2 AA, strong SEO, sub-3s LCP on 4G, and easy content authoring.

1) High-Level Architecture
- Frontend Web App: Next.js for hybrid SSR/SSG, edge rendering for marketing pages, CSR for dashboards. Global CDN for static assets.
- Backend API Layer: NestJS (Node.js) providing REST and/or GraphQL endpoints. Modular services: Auth, Content, Media, Search, Commerce, Forms, Analytics.
- Authentication & Authorization: OAuth2/Social login, email/password with WebAuthn, JWT for sessions, short-lived access + refresh tokens. RBAC with roles and fine-grained permissions.
- Data Storage:
  • Primary: PostgreSQL (normalized schema + JSONB for flexible metadata).
  • Cache: Redis for sessions, rate limiting, hot content, and job queues.
  • Search: OpenSearch/Elasticsearch or Algolia for full-text and faceted search.
  • Object Storage: S3-compatible bucket for media assets with image processing via serverless functions or CDN transforms.
- Asynchronous Processing: Message queue (RabbitMQ/SQS) for email, image processing, webhooks, analytics batching.
- Observability: Centralized logs, metrics, and tracing; error monitoring (Sentry/Datadog), RUM on frontend.
- CI/CD: GitHub Actions/GitLab CI with build/test/deploy pipelines. Environments: dev, staging, prod. Feature flags for controlled releases.
- Security: HTTPS/TLS, HSTS, CSP, CSRF protection, input validation, secret management (Vault/SM), WAF/CDN firewall. Regular dependency scanning.
- Scalability: Stateless API nodes behind a load balancer, horizontal scale via containers/Kubernetes. Database read replicas, connection pooling, and partitioning for analytics tables.

2) Database Design (PostgreSQL 16)
Core Entities (schema highlights):
- users(id PK, email UNIQUE, password_hash, display_name, status, created_at, updated_at)
- roles(id PK, name UNIQUE), user_roles(user_id FK, role_id FK)
- permissions(id PK, key UNIQUE), role_permissions(role_id FK, permission_id FK)
- sessions(id PK, user_id FK, refresh_token UNIQUE, ip, ua, expires_at, created_at)
- content_pages(id PK, slug UNIQUE, title, body, status, published_at, author_id FK, metadata JSONB)
- posts(id PK, slug UNIQUE, title, content, status, category_id FK, author_id FK, metadata JSONB)
- categories(id PK, name UNIQUE, slug UNIQUE)
- tags(id PK, name UNIQUE, slug UNIQUE); post_tags(post_id FK, tag_id FK)
- media_assets(id PK, storage_key UNIQUE, url, type, size, width, height, alt_text, uploaded_by FK, created_at)
- comments(id PK, entity_type, entity_id, user_id FK, body, status, created_at)
- forms(id PK, name UNIQUE, schema JSONB, active), form_submissions(id PK, form_id FK, data JSONB, status, submitted_at)
- products(id PK, sku UNIQUE, name, description, price DECIMAL, currency, stock INT, status, metadata JSONB)
- orders(id PK, user_id FK, status, total DECIMAL, currency, created_at, updated_at), order_items(order_id FK, product_id FK, quantity INT, price DECIMAL)
- payments(id PK, order_id FK, provider, status, amount DECIMAL, transaction_id UNIQUE, created_at)
- audit_logs(id PK, entity_type, entity_id, action, actor_id FK, changes JSONB, created_at)
- feature_flags(id PK, key UNIQUE, value JSONB, environment)
- analytics_events(id PK, user_id FK NULLABLE, session_id, event_name, properties JSONB, occurred_at TIMESTAMPTZ)
Indexes & Constraints:
- B-tree indexes on slugs, foreign keys, created_at for feed queries.
- GIN indexes on JSONB (metadata, properties) for flexible filtering.
- Partial indexes for status='published' on posts/content_pages.
- Time-based partitioning for analytics_events.
- FKs with ON DELETE CASCADE where appropriate (e.g., post_tags, order_items).

3) API Design
- REST for public endpoints (content delivery, product listing). GraphQL for internal dashboards and complex querying. Versioned APIs (v1, v2).
- Pagination (cursor-based preferred), filtering, sorting; OpenAPI/Swagger docs. Webhooks for order/payment updates and form submissions.

4) Caching & Performance
- Server-side caching: Redis for rendered HTML of high-traffic pages (short TTL), database query results, and search suggestions.
- CDN: Static asset caching, image resize, WebP/AVIF, HTTP/2/3. Preload critical resources, code-splitting, route-based chunks.
- Performance budgets: LCP < 2.5s, TTI < 4s, CLS < 0.1. Use Priority Hints, preconnect, and defer non-critical JS.

5) Security & Compliance
- OWASP Top 10 coverage, rate limiting per IP/user, bot protection, audit trails. GDPR/CCPA-ready data flows, cookie consent, data export/delete.

6) Deployment Model
- Containerized services (Docker). Optionally Kubernetes for production with autoscaling. Managed Postgres (e.g., RDS/Cloud SQL). IaC with Terraform. Blue/green or canary deployments via feature flags.

7) Content Management
- Headless CMS approach: Internal content tables + admin UI, or integrate a headless CMS (e.g., Strapi/Sanity) while retaining internal schema for critical data. Role-based authoring, draft/publish workflows, revision history.

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a robust Python program named Auto Complex Dataset Analysis that automatically analyzes and solves problems for a dataset located at complex.csv. The program must: 

Functional requirements:
1) Input handling and CLI
- Default dataset path: 'complex.csv'. Allow override via --input.
- Optional --target to specify the target column.
- Optional --task to force task type: one of ['classification', 'regression', 'clustering', 'anomaly'].
- Optional --test_size (default 0.2), --seed (default 42), --max_rows (default None to read full; if provided, sample rows), --output_dir (default './code/complex_dataset_analysis/artifacts').
- Validate arguments and provide helpful error messages.

2) Task auto-detection
- If --task is provided, use it.
- Else if --target is provided:
  * If target is numeric with more than 20 unique values → regression.
  * If target is binary or categorical with <= 20 unique categories → classification.
- Else (no target): attempt unsupervised:
  * clustering via KMeans (k selection via silhouette from k=2..8), and
  * anomaly detection via IsolationForest.

3) Data loading and type inference
- Read CSV with pandas; support large files with optional --max_rows sampling.
- Separate features and target if provided.
- Infer columns types into numeric and categorical using pandas dtypes and cardinality heuristics.
- Drop columns with near-constant values (e.g., same value ratio > 0.99) and report them.
- Handle duplicate rows by removing duplicates and reporting count.

4) Preprocessing pipeline
- Use ColumnTransformer and Pipeline from scikit-learn.
- Numeric: SimpleImputer(strategy='median'), StandardScaler (for models sensitive to scale, including KMeans).
- Categorical: SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent'), OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False).
- Preserve feature names via get_feature_names_out.

5) Model selection and training
- For classification: train LogisticRegression (liblinear for small datasets), RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier. Choose best by ROC-AUC if binary; else macro F1.
- For regression: train Ridge, RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor. Choose best by RMSE.
- Use cross-validation (StratifiedKFold for classification with n_splits=5; KFold for regression with n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed).
- Perform light hyperparameter search with RandomizedSearchCV where suitable (limit n_iter to keep runtime modest, e.g., 15).
- For clustering: KMeans with k in [2..8], evaluate silhouette score to choose k; refit on full data; save cluster centers and labels.
- For anomaly: IsolationForest (n_estimators=200, contamination='auto'), save anomaly scores and flags.

6) Evaluation and outputs
- Split train/test for supervised tasks using train_test_split(test_size, random_state=seed), stratify when classification.
- Metrics:
  * classification: accuracy, macro F1, ROC-AUC (if binary). Save classification report.
  * regression: RMSE, MAE, R2.
  * clustering: silhouette score for selected k; save per-sample labels.
  * anomaly: proportion of anomalies, score quantiles.
- Save artifacts:
  * best_model.pkl (joblib), preprocessor.pkl (joblib).
  * metrics.json with all scores and model details.
  * predictions.csv for supervised (include id/index, y_true if available, y_pred, and y_proba for binary).
  * clusters.csv for clustering (index, cluster_label); centers.json for centroids.
  * anomalies.csv for anomaly detection (index, anomaly_score, is_anomaly).
  * report.md summarizing dataset info, preprocessing decisions, selected model(s), metrics, and next steps.
- Ensure output_dir exists; create if missing.

7) Logging and robustness
- Configure logging (INFO level) with timestamps.
- Comprehensive try/except blocks around major stages with actionable messages.
- Validate that target exists when provided; error if invalid.
- Handle class imbalance: report class distribution; if severe imbalance (>90/10), enable class_weight='balanced' for LR and RF when applicable.

8) How-to/run instructions
- Provide argparse help and a docstring header explaining usage examples:
  Examples:
  - python auto_complex_dataset_analysis.py --input complex.csv --target Outcome
  - python auto_complex_dataset_analysis.py --input complex.csv --task clustering
  - python auto_complex_dataset_analysis.py --input complex.csv --target price --task regression --test_size 0.25

Implementation details:
- Use only standard Python, pandas, numpy, scikit-learn, joblib. Avoid external dependencies beyond these.
- Structure code with functions: load_data(), infer_types(), build_preprocessor(), select_and_train_supervised(), run_clustering(), run_anomaly_detection(), evaluate_classification(), evaluate_regression(), save_artifacts(), main().
- Ensure the script is executable from the command line and neatly organized, with clear comments.
- Keep resource usage reasonable and fail gracefully with clear messages.

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a robust Python script that analyzes global climate change trends over the last decade and forecasts the next decade, using authoritative Earth science datasets. Requirements:

1) Data sources (authoritative):
   - Global temperature anomaly (monthly): Prefer NASA GISTEMP V4 global mean anomalies table (CSV):
     https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/tabledata_v4/Global-mean_Ts_anomaly.csv
     Notes: Data are hundredths of °C. Columns: Year, Jan..Dec, J-D, etc. Use monthly columns, divide by 100 to get °C.
     Fallback: Berkeley Earth Global Land+Ocean monthly anomalies (if NASA fails):
     http://berkeleyearth.lbl.gov/auto/Global/Land_and_Ocean_complete.txt
     This file is space-delimited with headers; it includes Year, Month, "Monthly Anomaly (C)".
   - Atmospheric CO2 (monthly): NOAA GML Mauna Loa monthly averages (CSV):
     https://gml.noaa.gov/webdata/ccgg/trends/co2/co2_mm_mlo.csv
     Notes: File contains header lines starting with '#'. Use columns: year, month, decimal_date, average.

2) Scope and preprocessing:
   - Construct a monthly time series DataFrame from the last 10 complete years (rolling window relative to the latest available date in both datasets), aligned by year-month.
   - Temperature anomaly: Convert NASA hundredths °C to °C; for Berkeley Earth, already in °C. Create a single temp_anomaly column.
   - CO2: Use NOAA 'average' column; interpolate missing months if necessary.
   - Handle missing values with forward-fill/back-fill; drop months missing either temp or CO2 after reasonable imputation.

3) Modeling approach (transparent and interpretable):
   - Design matrix: [Intercept, time_trend_years, CO2_ppm, monthly seasonality dummies (Jan..Dec)].
   - Fit Ordinary Least Squares using numpy.linalg.lstsq (avoid heavy dependencies). Target: temp_anomaly (°C).
   - Report coefficients and R^2.

4) Forecasting:
   - Project CO2 for next 10 years monthly via linear trend estimated from the last decade CO2 data (simple linear regression of CO2 vs. time).
   - Create future monthly date index for next 120 months.
   - Use fitted model to predict temp anomaly for each future month.
   - Aggregate to annual means to report headline values.

5) Outputs:
   - Save merged historical last-decade dataset to ./outputs/historical_decade.csv.
   - Save monthly forecasts to ./outputs/forecast_monthly.csv and annual means to ./outputs/forecast_annual.csv.
   - Generate and save plots to ./outputs/:
       a) temp_anomaly_history_forecast.png (last decade + next decade)
       b) co2_history_forecast.png
   - Print to console:
       - Decadal warming rate (°C per decade) from the time_trend coefficient.
       - Projected global mean temperature anomaly for year +10 (annual mean).
       - Projected CO2 level for year +10 (annual mean).
       - R^2 of the regression.
   - Include a brief textual summary at the end citing data sources and noting limitations.

6) Robustness:
   - Implement try/except for NASA fetch; if it fails, use Berkeley Earth fallback parser (ignore header/comment lines starting with '%', '#', or text; parse columns by whitespace, expecting Year and Month and Anomaly).
   - For NOAA CO2, use pandas.read_csv with comment='#'.
   - Ensure script creates ./outputs/ directory if it doesn't exist.
   - Use only standard libraries plus numpy, pandas, matplotlib; avoid non-standard packages.

7) Documentation:
   - Add clear comments and a module-level docstring summarizing the methodology, references (NASA GISTEMP V4, NOAA GML CO2, and the general Earth-science context e.g., IPCC AR6 for background trends), and assumptions.

8) Final behavior:
   - When run, the script should fetch data, build the aligned last-decade dataset, fit the model, forecast the next decade, save outputs and plots, and print the summary metrics.

Make the code concise but reliable, with informative logging and graceful fallbacks. Use UTC and yyyy-mm formatting for dates in outputs.
